What is lazy evaluation in Spark and why does it matter?
Transformations (filter, map, join) build a logical plan but execute nothing. Execution only starts when an action is called (count, show, write). This lets Catalyst optimise the entire plan before running — e.g. pushing filters before joins to reduce data early.

What is the difference between a transformation and an action?
Transformations return a new DataFrame and are lazy — filter, select, join, groupBy, withColumn. Actions trigger execution and return a result — count, show, collect, write, take. Every Spark job ends with an action.

What is a DAG in Spark? How is it split into stages?
DAG = Directed Acyclic Graph. It's the execution plan Spark builds from your transformations. The DAG Scheduler splits it into stages at shuffle boundaries — every wide transformation (groupBy, join, distinct) creates a new stage. Within a stage, all tasks run in parallel.

What is the difference between narrow and wide transformations?
Narrow: each input partition maps to exactly one output partition. No data movement. Examples: filter, map, select, withColumn, union. Wide: output partitions depend on multiple input partitions — requires a shuffle (data moves across network). Examples: groupBy, join, distinct, repartition, orderBy.

What does the Catalyst optimizer do?
Catalyst takes your logical plan and applies optimization rules before execution: predicate pushdown (filters moved earlier), column pruning (unused columns dropped), join reordering, and constant folding. It then generates multiple physical plans and picks the cheapest one based on cost estimation.

What is the difference between RDD, DataFrame, and Dataset?
RDD: low-level, no schema, no Catalyst optimization, full control. DataFrame: distributed table with schema, Catalyst optimized, most common in PySpark. Dataset: type-safe DataFrame (Scala/Java only — not available in Python). In PySpark you almost always use DataFrames.

How do you handle data skew in Spark?
Skew = one partition has far more data than others, causing one task to run much longer. Solutions: 1) Salting — add a random prefix to the skewed key to spread data across more partitions. 2) Broadcast join — if one side is small, broadcast it to avoid shuffle entirely. 3) AQE skew join — Spark 3.x detects and splits skewed partitions automatically.
from pyspark.sql.functions import col, rand, concat, lit

df_salted = df.withColumn("salted_key",
    concat(col("join_key"), lit("_"), (rand()*10).cast("int")))

What is the difference between repartition() and coalesce()?
repartition(n): full shuffle, evenly redistributes data, can increase or decrease partitions. coalesce(n): no shuffle, merges partitions locally, can only decrease partitions. Use coalesce when writing fewer output files (cheaper). Use repartition when you need even distribution before a heavy operation.

What is a broadcast join and when do you use it?
A broadcast join sends the smaller DataFrame to every executor, so the join happens locally without a shuffle. Use when one side is small (default threshold 10MB, configurable). Eliminates the most expensive operation in Spark.
from pyspark.sql.functions import broadcast

df_result = large_df.join(broadcast(small_df), "id")

What is caching and when should you use it?
cache() / persist() stores a DataFrame in memory so it's not recomputed on every action. Use when a DataFrame is used multiple times in the same job. Don't cache everything — it wastes memory and can spill to disk. Always unpersist() when done.
df.cache()
df.count()  # triggers caching
df.filter(...).show()  # reads from cache
df.unpersist()  # free memory

Follow-up: "What's the difference between cache() and persist()?" — cache() = MEMORY_AND_DISK by default. persist() lets you specify storage level: MEMORY_ONLY, DISK_ONLY, MEMORY_AND_DISK, etc.

What is AQE (Adaptive Query Execution)?
AQE (Spark 3.0+) re-optimises the query plan at runtime using actual data statistics from completed stages. Three key features: 1) dynamically coalesces small shuffle partitions, 2) converts sort-merge joins to broadcast joins when a side turns out to be small, 3) handles skewed joins by splitting large partitions.
Enable with: spark.conf.set("spark.sql.adaptive.enabled", "true"). On Databricks it's on by default. Mention this shows you're up to date with Spark 3.x.

What is exactly-once semantics in Spark Streaming?
Three delivery guarantees: at-most-once (data may be lost), at-least-once (data may be duplicated), exactly-once (data processed exactly once, no loss, no duplicates). Spark Structured Streaming achieves exactly-once by combining checkpointing (tracks offsets) with idempotent sinks or transactional writes.
You have this on your CV — "built Kafka + Spark Structured Streaming pipelines with exactly-once delivery." Be ready to explain HOW: checkpointing + Kafka offset tracking + writing to Delta Lake (which supports ACID transactions).

What is checkpointing in Spark Streaming?
Checkpointing saves the state of a streaming query to durable storage (ADLS, S3, HDFS). Tracks: 1) offsets read from source (e.g. Kafka partition offsets), 2) intermediate state for stateful operations (aggregations, joins). On failure, the query restarts from the last checkpoint — no reprocessing from the beginning.
df.writeStream \
  .format("delta") \
  .option("checkpointLocation", "/mnt/checkpoints/my_stream") \
  .start("/mnt/output/my_table")

What is watermarking and why is it needed?
Watermarking handles late-arriving data in streaming. It tells Spark: "wait up to X time for late data, then discard anything older." Without watermarking, Spark would keep state for all past events forever, causing unbounded memory growth. Watermark = event_time threshold below which late records are dropped.
df.withWatermark("event_time", "10 minutes") \
  .groupBy(window(col("event_time"), "5 minutes")) \
  .count()
Key follow-up: "What's the difference between event time and processing time?" — Event time = when the event actually happened (in the data). Processing time = when Spark received/processed it. Always use event time for accurate analytics.

